TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Efficient Use of an Imperfect Forecast
AU  - Thompson, Howard E.
AU  - Beranek, William
Y1  - 1966/11/01
PY  - 1966
DA  - 1966/11/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.13.3.233
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.13.3.233
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 233
EP  - 243
VL  - 13
IS  - 3
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper illustrates how individual forecasts and forecasting techniques may be evaluated by the use of established decision theory. Given the probability distribution of the forecast error, we first find the optimal strategy for a decision process, i.e., how to make the most efficient use of a forecast. After expressing the expected profit of the optimal strategies in terms of the probability of a correct forecast, we illustrate how to find (1) the value of an imperfect forecast, and (2) the value of a forecasting technique. With this information, we can then determine when to use a forecast, the maximum amount to pay for both a forecast and a forecasting method, and the conditions under which it is worthwhile to attempt to improve the accuracy of a forecasting method.
AB  - This paper illustrates how individual forecasts and forecasting techniques may be evaluated by the use of established decision theory. Given the probability distribution of the forecast error, we first find the optimal strategy for a decision process, i.e., how to make the most efficient use of a forecast. After expressing the expected profit of the optimal strategies in terms of the probability of a correct forecast, we illustrate how to find (1) the value of an imperfect forecast, and (2) the value of a forecasting technique. With this information, we can then determine when to use a forecast, the maximum amount to pay for both a forecast and a forecasting method, and the conditions under which it is worthwhile to attempt to improve the accuracy of a forecasting method.
